TY  - JOUR
T1  - Imperfect Information and Wage Inertia in the Business Cycle
AU  - Gertler, Mark
Y1  - 1982/10/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261103
DO  - 10.1086/261103
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 967
EP  - 987
VL  - 90
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Nominal wages have less variation about a trend than the money supply does, and the variation is more persistent. This inertia in the nominal wage is often cited as the principal source of stagflation. This paper explains the phenomenon by appealing to temporary wage inflexibility in an environment where agents cannot directly disentangle permanent versus transitory movements in key state variables. A wage equation results that is a distributed lag of previous values of the state variables, including money. Nominal wage variation becomes less sensitive to the money supply as agents' ability to detect the permanent evolution of the money supply declines.
AB  - Nominal wages have less variation about a trend than the money supply does, and the variation is more persistent. This inertia in the nominal wage is often cited as the principal source of stagflation. This paper explains the phenomenon by appealing to temporary wage inflexibility in an environment where agents cannot directly disentangle permanent versus transitory movements in key state variables. A wage equation results that is a distributed lag of previous values of the state variables, including money. Nominal wage variation becomes less sensitive to the money supply as agents' ability to detect the permanent evolution of the money supply declines.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261103
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261103
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Directly Unproductive, Profit-Seeking (DUP) Activities
AU  - Bhagwati, Jagdish N.
Y1  - 1982/10/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261104
DO  - 10.1086/261104
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 988
EP  - 1002
VL  - 90
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper propses directly unproductive, profit-seeking (DUP) activities as a general concept that embraces a wide range of recently analyzed economic activities, including the subset of rent-seeking activities considered by Krueger. It then proceeds to provide a synthesis and generalization of the welfare-theoretic analysis of such activities by developing a fourfold categorization of cases depending on the levels of distortions before and after the DUP activity. Thus a unification and overview of the subject are achieved.
AB  - This paper propses directly unproductive, profit-seeking (DUP) activities as a general concept that embraces a wide range of recently analyzed economic activities, including the subset of rent-seeking activities considered by Krueger. It then proceeds to provide a synthesis and generalization of the welfare-theoretic analysis of such activities by developing a fourfold categorization of cases depending on the levels of distortions before and after the DUP activity. Thus a unification and overview of the subject are achieved.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261104
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261104
Y2  - 2024/03/22
